    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_179742387" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/179742387" />
    <a title="slowliv" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5690694-slowliv"><img alt="slowliv" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_50x66-632230dc9882b4352d753eedf9396530.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/179742387?book_show_action=true">Jun 26, 2011</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="slowliv" class="user" itemprop="url" name="slowliv" href="/user/show/5690694-slowliv">slowliv</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5690694-slowliv?shelf=historical-fiction">historical-fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer179742387" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2596202307579953233">As the writer claimed, this book is a historical fiction thus one can’t really argue on its historical accuracy. However, to my disappointment there are quite some significant deviations between historical facts and what were written in this book.<br/><br/>Shors wrote that Jahanara was wedded to a sadistic silver merchant. The marriage was not going well and she then had an affair with the Taj Mahal’s architect; Isa. Jahanara and Isa later had a daughter named after Jahanara’s mother; Arjumand.<br/><br/>The fact is</span>
  <span id="freeText2596202307579953233" style="display:none">As the writer claimed, this book is a historical fiction thus one can’t really argue on its historical accuracy. However, to my disappointment there are quite some significant deviations between historical facts and what were written in this book.<br /><br />Shors wrote that Jahanara was wedded to a sadistic silver merchant. The marriage was not going well and she then had an affair with the Taj Mahal’s architect; Isa. Jahanara and Isa later had a daughter named after Jahanara’s mother; Arjumand.<br /><br />The fact is Jahanara never married. She never had any children not to mention grandchildren. When she died, her belongings were inherited by one of Dara Shikoh’s daughter.<br /><br />Shors also wrote that Jahanara use the opportunity of Shah Jahan’s funeral to run away to Calcutta. Well, no. She did continue to serve the empire even by then it was ruled by Aurangzeb.<br /><br />Well, I wish Shors dig into the clash between Jahanara, Aurangzeb, and Roshanara, which I believe could be quite interesting rather than dramatizing the non-existent Jahanara’s romantic life with Isa. Roshanara was not even mentioned in this novel!<br /><br />One more thing, Shors kept referring to Agra Fort as Red Fort. Those two forts might look similar but Red Fort was in Delhi while Agra Fort as its name was in Agra.<br /><br />And by the way, Polo was originated from Iran, not Agra.</span>
  <a data-text-id="2596202307579953233" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


